          <div id="id2" style="height: 1191px; left: 30px; position: absolute; top: 99px; width: 902px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
            <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_902_1191" style="padding: 0px; ">
              <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">And since I am on vacation, here’s an Indian puzzle freshly roasted for those caffeine/brainiac geeks. <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">Consider an average girl looking for a suitable match and she interviews around 100 people to select the best match. Once she rejects someone she can’t call him back. The suitable mates arrive in random order for instance {good, bad, worst, bad,bad,good....etc}. What strategy she can employ to make sure she maximizes her probability of ending up with best mate. <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">Of course this is a mathematical puzzle, which to put into clear perspective, let’s assume <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">N = Number of candidates, she has lined up (She can stop whenever she wants)<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">R = Number of candidates she decides she has to reject, but will interview them anyway<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">After rejecting R candidates, the R+1’th candidate comes, what is the probability that he is the best one - <span class="style">1/N</span><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">When R+2’th candidate comes it means she has already rejected R+1’th candidate, and so the probability of him being best is still 1/N, but what is the probability of R+1’th candidate being worst in the line (past candidates) 1...R+1. It is R/(R+1). This is a subtle conclusion so let me expand....<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">Let’s say R = 3, and first three candidates are Adam (always the first), Animesh (always second), Linus. The ranking order she had till now was that “Linus” was the best. When 4th candidate comes (R+1), then she decides that R+1th is worst than Linus(best so far), so she has to move on. So probability of best candidate being in first three out of total 4 = 3/4 = 75%, and thus the expression R/(R+1)...and so on for R+2...<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">So probability of choosing R+2 candidate and him being the best is =&gt; 1/N x R/(R+1)<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">Adding up all these probabilities we have,<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">1/N + 1/N x R/(R+1) + 1/N x (R)/(R+2) + 1/N x (R)/(R+3)<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">or (R/N) [1/R + 1/(R+1) + 1/(R+2) + .......]<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">it can be written as<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">(R/N)[ Summation (i=1 to N (1/i)) - Summation (i=1 to R) (1/i-1)) <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">This reduces to <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">-(R/N) Log(R/N)<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">The maximum can be found by differentiating this function. The result comes out to be, N/e or 1/e of fraction of candidates should be interviewed and rejected. So R = N/e<br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">For N = 100, it comes out to be, approx 36 candidates. This gives probability of 57%. (&gt; 40%  passing marks!). <br /></p>
                <p class="paragraph_style">Nice algorithm won’t u say, but does it work in Real life....you should ask her.... ;)<br /></p>
